1.0 Introduction/Background
In 1981, Terry Hayamizu established the Asian Pacific Student Association (APSA), an organization that exists to empower and improve the Asian American and Pacific Islander community at the University of California, Irvine. The Asian Pacific Student Associations (APSA) goals include promoting diversity throughout the community at large through its commitment to education, advocacy, community outreach, and active political participation. APSA strives to achieve equality in a multicultural society. Our team believes that the organization can further stress these values through a redesign of their current website. 

2.0 Business Objective
The Asian Pacific Student Association (APSA) advocates for cultural sensitivity and awareness throughout campus. The website redesign project will support the Asian Pacific Student Associations (APSA) goals by increasing the publics awareness about the organization through a website that is more visually appealing and informative. By completely redesigning the website, we hope to increase the general knowledge about APSA and to empower the clubs online presence, helping the organization attract new members. This project will also improve the general functionality of the website, making it more accessible and easier for club members and potential prospects to use. 

3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement
The Asian Pacific Student Association (APSA) currently has a website and uses several other social media sites. At the moment, APSA uses a website that utilizes Jimdo, a free website builder. Jimdo is an excellent website builder that provides ease of use in every way and aims to remove all barriers that enable users from creating their own professional website. The primary use of this website is for club members to advertise and promote club related activities and events. The website also functions as a way for people who express interests in joining to learn more about the organization. However, APSA is not a well known organization on campus. The current website appears dreary, bland, and poorly maintained making it difficult for APSA to properly publicize and draw attention to new members. There is an opportunity to increase the organizations presence and popularity on campus by redesigning the website to expand viewership and bring more interest to APSA. APSA can also further improve its current website by utilizing the many different functionalities provided by Jimdo.


4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints
The proposed new redesign to the APSA website must be useful, effective, and beneficial for APSA. The redesign must generate a greater visitor frequency, motivate more people in the community to support and engage in events held by APSA. The current APSA board and members must support the project and agree to using the new redesign in place of the current website. The new website will require a webmaster to manage and maintain the websites content, as well as improving and continually updating information related to the organization. Although a webmaster is necessary to bring the new system up to date, the website should require very little technical support for the day-to-day user. The new website must be completed by the end of Winter Quarter 2013 and must be accessible through the web. 

5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation
There are 3 options regarding this project:

1. Do nothing and instead publicize the APSA website in its current state. The club recruits new members throughout the year and can continue to function without the new redesign.

2. Gain access to the current APSA website and work off of features already existing and add any additional new features including redesigning the current layout. Changes would include utilizing more colors, reorganizing information placement, adding more graphics and images to improve visual appeal, and incorporating APSAs social media accounts on the main website. 

3. Consider the current APSA website scrapped and build an entirely new website intended to fit APSAs goals. This new website would not be publish online, but instead be only viewable for APSA to review. We recommend using a webmaster to keep the website up to date.

6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements
The objective in the redesign of APSAs website is to help visitors gain a deeper understanding of why APSA exists. The new website needs to perfectly align with this vision. Our team will accomplish this by analyzing how the websites of popular organizations on campus succeed. The main features in creation of a website redesign for the Asian Pacific Student Association (APSA) include the following:

1. Adding more images to the the website in order to make it more visually appealing. The homepage will feature a slideshow showing pictures of members actively participating in club activities. 

2. Making the links to APSAs social media websites more visual and stand out more. This can be done through the use of icons. The Twitter feed needs to be made more visible.

3. Removing any advertisements shown on the homepage.

4. Adding brighter colors to the page to make it more visually appealing. The current site uses mainly grey and black. By making the website more colorful, it would create a more exciting experience for visitors. 

7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis
This project will require little to no budget. However, skills and knowledge in the field of web design would prove to be helpful in the implementation process. This estimate is based on the basic costs and works that come with designing a web page. The designers for the website are not asking to be paid for this project, but are rather doing it out of the goodness of their hearts for the purpose of aiding APSA in its quest to attract more members and increase its presence at the University of California, Irvine. After the project is completed, the Asian Pacific Student Association should appoint a webmaster from within their club to take on the task of continually updating the websites content and ensuring its design is on par with the websites of other organizations.

8.0 Schedule Estimate
The organization would like to see this project completed before the end of Winter Quarter 2013. This is approximately 10 weeks. We also assume that the new website design will have a useful life of at least three years.

9.0 Potential Risks
There are some risks involved with this project. The biggest risk is that a website redesign may not change the visitor frequency at all and will fail at increasing APSAs presence on campus. The new design could also possibly turn out even worse than the original design, unsuccessful in being more informative and visually appealing. Any changes made to the website holds the risk of possibly crashing the website, and in the worst scenario, deleting all information on the website and forcing a complete start from scratch. The clubs board and members could also show little interest in implementing a new redesign. The main business risk for this project is investing the necessary time and work into the project to complete the main objective of creating a website that improves APSAs presence on campus.
